@JaredBanyard [this](https://github.com/JakeWharton/sdk-manager-plugin/blob/master/src/main/groovy/com/jakewharton/sdkmanager/internal/SdkResolver.groovy#L35) looks more like it downloads it to ~/.android-sdk if not available and it also uses this sdk to download the requried components.

and if an sdk is found (eg [if ANDROID_HOME is set](https://github.com/JakeWharton/sdk-manager-plugin/blob/master/src/main/groovy/com/jakewharton/sdkmanager/internal/SdkResolver.groovy#L63))  it uses this sdk and also updates missing components inside this sdk.

and i confim this behaviour on my build server using 0.10.+ of this plugin in my build.gradle it created an ~./.android-sdk installation (and this is far from my project folder!) and after executing the commands (to update the sdk) in my above comment this plugin was wroking well again.

@JaredBanyard `has anybody actually tracked down the specific issue inside the Groovy code?` yes. i did. ;)

if this plugins does not find an installed sdk (via ANDROID_HOME environment variable or in ~/.android-sdk) it downloads the sdk files and extracts them to ~/-android-sdk. the problem is that this downloaded sdk is outdated (there is a [commit](https://github.com/JakeWharton/sdk-manager-plugin/commit/ba56d4aab2983d007ed81b7973640f37e76f9715) to download the newer sdk version but that is not yet released). this outdated sdk is not able to get the v20 dependencies mentioned in this issue. and as the sdk is not able to get them, the sdkmanager is unable to get them too, as it calls the [android sdk tools](https://github.com/JakeWharton/sdk-manager-plugin/blob/master/src/main/groovy/com/jakewharton/sdkmanager/internal/AndroidCommand.groovy#L47) to load the dependencies.

therefore the fix would be: the sdkmanager should make sure that the `Android SDK Tools` are up to date

